title: Stock market today: Dow, S&P 500, Nasdaq slide after Powell flags Fed's challenge, 'highly valued' stocks
content:
The S&P 500 (^GSPC) fell about 0.6%, and the tech-heavy Nasdaq Composite (^IXIC) lost almost 1%.
Powell suggested during a speech in Rhode Island that the central bank would move cautiously after resuming rate cuts last week, noting the challenge of balancing its dual mandate at the moment.
"Near-term risks to inflation are tilted to the upside and risks to employment to the downside — a challenging situation.
Later, in a question-and-answer session, he noted that "by many measures, for example, equity prices are fairly highly valued."
Powell's comments set the stage for the release on Friday of the Fed's preferred inflation gauge, the Personal Consumption Expenditures index.

title: Stock market today: Nasdaq, Dow, S&P 500 waver with divided Fed, Alibaba in focus
content:
US stocks fell on Wednesday as Wall Street digested mixed messaging from Fed officials on interest rates.
Debate over the prospects for US interest rate cuts — the big focus for markets right now — appeared to pressure stocks.
Fed Chair Jerome Powell reiterated in a speech on Tuesday that the central bank would proceed cautiously on further rate cuts, even as he left the door open to more easing.
Markets are watching for reassurance that inflation isn't posing a threat to high expectations for two more rate cuts this year.
Meanwhile, some tech stocks are showing gains despite a broader drop across the Nasdaq, which snapped a winning streak on Tuesday amid losses for the "Magnificent Seven" Big Tech stocks.

title: Micron set to report Q4 earnings in latest test of AI trade
content:
Micron (MU) stock rose early on Wednesday after the chipmaker reported fiscal fourth quarter earnings that surpassed Wall Street's expectations.
Micron's fiscal fourth quarter revenue of $11.3 billion was ahead of the $11.15 billion expected by analysts polled by Bloomberg.
The Idaho-based memory chipmaker — whose semiconductors are used alongside Nvidia's chips in AI data centers — saw adjusted earnings per share of $3.03 for the three months ending Aug. 28, more than the $2.84 projected.
The beat was fueled by the AI data center boom, company executives said, with data centers representing 40% of the chipmaker's total revenue in the fourth quarter.
The company guided for first quarter revenue between $12.2 billion and $12.8 billion, more than the $11.9 billion expected by analysts tracked by Bloomberg.

content:

Debate over the prospects for US interest rate cuts — the big focus for markets right now — appeared to pressure stocks.

Meanwhile, some tech stocks are showing gains despite a broader drop across the Nasdaq, which snapped a winning streak on Tuesday amid losses for the "Magnificent Seven" Big Tech stocks.

title: Micron set to report Q4 earnings in latest test of AI trade
content:
Micron (MU) stock rose early on Wednesday after the chipmaker reported fiscal fourth quarter earnings that surpassed Wall Street's expectations.
Micron's fiscal fourth quarter revenue of $11.3 billion was ahead of the $11.15 billion expected by analysts polled by Bloomberg.
The Idaho-based memory chipmaker — whose semiconductors are used alongside Nvidia's chips in AI data centers — saw adjusted earnings per share of $3.03 for the three months ending Aug. 28, more than the $2.84 projected.
The beat was fueled by the AI data center boom, company executives said, with data centers representing 40% of the chipmaker's total revenue in the fourth quarter.
The company guided for first quarter revenue between $12.2 billion and $12.8 billion, more than the $11.9 billion expected by analysts tracked by Bloomberg.

title: Stock market today: Dow, S&P 500, Nasdaq futures edge up after Wall Street's record-setting rally stalls
content:
US stocks fell on Wednesday as Wall Street digested mixed messaging from Fed officials on interest rates.
Debate over the prospects for US interest rate cuts — the big focus for markets right now — appeared to pressure stocks.
Fed Chair Jerome Powell reiterated in a speech on Tuesday that the central bank would proceed cautiously on further rate cuts, even as he left the door open to more easing.
Markets are watching for reassurance that inflation isn't posing a threat to high expectations for two more rate cuts this year.
Meanwhile, some tech stocks are showing gains despite a broader drop across the Nasdaq, which snapped a winning streak on Tuesday amid losses for the "Magnificent Seven" Big Tech stocks.

title: Micron set to report Q4 earnings in latest test of AI trade
content:
Micron (MU) stock rose early on Wednesday after the chipmaker reported fiscal fourth quarter earnings that surpassed Wall Street's expectations.
Micron's fiscal fourth quarter revenue of $11.3 billion was ahead of the $11.15 billion expected by analysts polled by Bloomberg.
The Idaho-based memory chipmaker — whose semiconductors are used alongside Nvidia's chips in AI data centers — saw adjusted earnings per share of $3.03 for the three months ending Aug. 28, more than the $2.84 projected.
The beat was fueled by the AI data center boom, company executives said, with data centers representing 40% of the chipmaker's total revenue in the fourth quarter.
The company guided for first quarter revenue between $12.2 billion and $12.8 billion, more than the $11.9 billion expected by analysts tracked by Bloomberg.

title: New Blood Pressure Guidelines Mean You May Now Have Hypertension
content:
Systolic blood pressure, the top number, represents the pressure in the blood vessels when the heart is squeezing blood into the body.
Diastolic blood pressure, the bottom number, is the pressure in the blood vessels when the heart is relaxing.
Now, patients are categorized as having "elevated blood pressure" if their blood pressure is 120-129 over less than 80 mm Hg, or stage 1 hypertension if they are 130-139/80-89.
On average, for every additional 30 minutes of aerobic exercise a person gets per week, systolic blood pressure decreases by 2 mm Hg and diastolic blood pressure drops by 1 mm Hg, with the largest reduction occurring at 150 minutes of dynamic exercise per week.
These include healthy diet, regular exercise, stopping or avoiding smoking, sleeping seven to nine hours per night, and controlling weight, cholesterol, blood sugar, and blood pressure.

title: Meta to Invest ‘Tens of Millions’ to Combat State-Level AI Bills
content:
Meta is reportedly investing “tens of millions” in its new super PAC dedicated to combating state-level proposals to regulate artificial intelligence (AI) and other technologies.
There have been 1,100 state-level tech policy proposals introduced this year, according to the report.
Politico reported Aug. 26 that Meta launched a California super PAC called Mobilizing Economic Transformation Across California that will support candidates for state offices who favor AI innovation.
When the Senate rejected the proposed 10-year moratorium on state-level AI regulations, it did so in a 99-1 vote.
Some of those who criticized the proposal flagged concerns about keeping states from regulating a powerful and potentially disruptive technology.

title: Netflix Stock Upgraded To Buy, Retakes Key Level
content:
Netflix (NFLX) stock rose above a key support level Wednesday after getting an upgrade from a Wall Street analyst.
Loop Capital Markets analyst Alan Gould upgraded Netflix to buy from hold and raised his price target to 1,350 from 1,150.
On the stock market today, Netflix stock rose 2.3% to close at 1,228.50.
Netflix stock is in a 12-week flat base with a buy point of 1,341.15, according to IBD MarketSurge charts.
Further, Netflix stock is on IBD's Leaderboard.

title: Why Netflix (NFLX) Stock Is Gaining Today?
content:
Sep 17 - Netflix (NASDAQ:NFLX) ticked higher about 1.5% on Wednesday after Bernstein reiterated its Outperform rating and $1,390 price target, easing investor worries about the company's content supply.
The note came as Wall Street weighed the potential impact of a possible deal between Paramount Global (PARA) and Warner Bros.
Both studios supply licensed content to Netflix, raising concerns that a merger could disrupt those relationships.
Moreover, Loop Capital's Alan Gould also shifted his view on Netflix to "Buy" from "Hold" and lifted the price target to $1,350 from $1,150.
For Paramount and Warner Bros.
